Modify template type inference at callsites to substitute the bound of a generic type when the inferred value of the template type doesn't match the bound.

Modify `GlobalNamespace` to prevent property collapsing on "implicitly aliased values".

To prevent code-size regressions, this behaviour change is guarded by "--assume_no_static_inheritance".

Introduce "--assume_no_static_inheritance" which will later be used to tune some optimizations with respect to the possiblity of static inheritance.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=266013293

~20% of the RemoveUsedCode pass' runtime is verify the set of known getter/setter definitions.  Since they can only be removed it is safe to defer this, it is force to run after collapse properties, disambiguate properties, property renaming, so there will be opportunities to take advantage of improved code removal.

If we find it value to run during the optimization loop in general, we can trigger independently only if the AST has actually changed (before this CL, it would verify even if RemoveUnusedCode did nothing itself).

No-op: Produce fewer unnecessary unions when parsing JSType expressions.

Previously, all name references were treated as possibly nullable when parsed into types, even though many references are explicitly non-null. This change checks for explicit non-nullability and prevents a union from being created if so. The old behaviour that stripped null from parsed types is retained to cover other cases.

There are also substantial readability improvements to the modified code, but they should be non-semantic.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=264629613

Add @param annotations to all setters generated in source AST by Polymer

Polymer pass generates setters in the source AST without @param annotations.
This causes the param type to be referred from the extern interface (that
Polymer generates also).

Due to a bug, PolymerPass creates references to local types in
the externs. The fix for that bug(in process) will make the extern types "{?}".
Hence, without @param annotation in the source AST's setters, they will end up
using the extern type {?}. So we must annotate the setters with @param.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=264452184

Allow duplicate symbol declarations in the JSModuleGraph

Currently when building the map of <Symbol, CompilerInput> we don't check if
there's a pre-existing entry. This has the effect of silently dropping all but
the last file in the list. While having multiple inputs declare the symbols is
invalid, it's shouldn't be silently ignored. By allowing them through the
JSModuleGraph we can accurately check for dupes later on in the compilation.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=261349974

Handle preserved comments when non-import statements are replaced

Currently all comments related to import statements are handled when we replace their corresponding AST nodes in SuggestedFix. When AST nodes corresponding to non-import statements are replaced (i.e inserted, moved, deleted, etc), their preserved comments must be handled appropriately.

With this change, I am adjusting the startPosition of a node in order to include the nonJSDoc comments attached to it every time a replacement of that node happens.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=261238859

Respect the scope of function declarations when normalizing.

In strict mode, function declarations in local scope are block scoped (like const/let), but NormalizePass incorrectly assumes they're function scoped (like var) and rewrites them as `var x = function() { ... }`. This breaks code when the function shadows a variable in an outer scope.

Fortunately, MakeDeclaredNamesUnique already handles function declarations correctly. Therefore, we can fix this bug by uniquifying names before other normalizations, so that any introduced `var`s are guaranteed not to shadow other variables.

Note that it wouldn't be possible to fix this by rewriting function declarations into a `let x = function() { ... }` instead, since normalization occurs after transpilation and this would break pre-ES6 output.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=257826830

Fix incorrect property collapse leading to a crash in VarCheck.

CollapseProperties will currently transform `var a = x || {b: 1}; var t = a.b` into `var a = x || {b: 1}; var t = a$b`, which causes a crash because `a$b` is never declared. A similar issue exists when the initializer is a ternary expression.

We should back off from collapsing property reads/writes when the property is declared in an or-expression or ternary-expression, since the declaration itself is never collapsed. However, property writes to undeclared properties are still safe to collapse, e.g. `var a = x || {b: 1}; a.c = 2` => `var a = x || {b: 1}; var a$c = 2`.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=255996993

Improve .i.js generation for Polymer Behaviors.

JS Compiler incremental compilation works by simplifying down each file to just what's needed for type-checking, so that it runs faster.

By default, object literal property right-hand-sides are simplified to "0", since the value doesn't usually matter. However, in the case of Polymer Behaviors the RHS does matter, because the PolymerPass uses it to understand which properties the behavior is going to set on the Polymer Elements that apply it.

This change preserves any property called "properties" on an object literal that is annotated with @polymerBehavior, and simplifies it so that only the necessary type information is preserved.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=255217202

Avoid converting $.foo to $['foo'] for method calls

Polymer classes have a `$` property that is used as a dictionary-like object. Client code often does stuff like `this.$.someProp` to access these properties. Left unmodified, JSCompiler would complain about these, because it doesn't have sufficient type information on `this.$` to know what properties exist on it. So, the Polymer pass converts `this.$.someProp` to `this.$['someProp']`, which JSCompiler won't complain about, because it doesn't look into the values used for bracket access.

The logic of the Polymer pass sometimes does this conversion when it shouldn't, because it cannot tell which properties named `$` really belong to a Polymer object and which don't. This is a problem for some method calls that are accessed as something.$.someMethod().

This CL makes the Polymer pass a bit smarter by avoiding the conversion when the `something.$.someProp` is the callee of a function call. None of the properties of a Polymer `$` property should be functions to call, so this avoids incorrect conversion for those cases.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=251496849

Update to Truth 0.45, and address deprecations.

Renames may include:
- containsAllOf => containsAtLeast
- containsAllIn => containsAtLeastElementsIn
- isSameAs => isSameInstanceAs
- isOrdered => isInOrder
- isStrictlyOrdered => isInStrictOrder

The other major change is to change custom subjects to extend raw Subject instead of supplying type parameters. The type parameters are being removed from Subject. This CL will temporarily produce rawtypes warnings, which will go away when I remove the type parameters (as soon as this batch of CLs is submitted).

Some CLs in this batch also migrate calls away from actualAsString(). Its literal replacement is `"<" + actual + ">"` (unless an object overrides actualCustomStringRepresentation()), but usually I've made a larger change, such as switching from an old-style "Not true that..." failure message to one generated with the Fact API. In that case, the new code usually contains a direct reference to this.actual (a field that I occasionally had to create). Another larger change I sometimes made is to switch from a manual check-and-fail approach to instead use check(...). And sometimes I just remove a withMessage() call that's no longer necessary now that the code uses check(...), or I introduce a check(...) call. (An assertion made with check(...) automatically includes the actual value from the original subject, so there's no need to set it again with withMessage().)

Finally, there's one CL in this batch in which I migrate a Correspondence subclass to instead use Correspondence.from.

MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=248202655

Create NodeUtil.getBooleanValue by merging 2 methods

This merges two confusingly name methods into one,
getImpureBooleanValue() and getLiteralBooleanValue().

getImpureBooleanValue() could successfully calculate values for more
complex expressions than getLiteralBooleanValue() could and delegated
to getLiteralBooleanValue() for cases it didn't specifically handle.

The merged method is intended to act like getImpureBooleanValue()
did, so the code that previously called getLiteralBooleanValue() will
see fewer UNKNOWN cases. This should be a win, since it should enable
more optimizations.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe

Use getLiteralBooleanValue() where we don't care about side-effects

In a couple of places we've been using getPureBooleanValue() in order
to exclude the broader logic of getImpureBooleanValue(), but we don't
actually care about side-effects. Using getLiteralBooleanValue()
is more appropriate in those places, and unblocks refactoring of the
side effect logic methods.

CheckSuspiciousCode had a comment specifically saying it wanted to
ignore side-effects just above the call to getPureBooleanValue()

Change `FunctionType` to print as "(typeof Foo)" when the type is associated with the definition of an instance type.

This condition corresponds to constructors or interfaces with a known source location and reflects the use of these functions as namespaces. It makes specific distinction between "the Foo constructor" and "some constructor of Foo's". The latter still prints as "function(new:Foo): undefined".

One of the goals is to make the printed types of static methods less verbose and more understandable. Example "function(this:(typeof Foo), string): number".

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=245086325

Optimize O(n^2) property lookups in getTopDefiningInterface to be linear (where n is number of ancestors).

getTopDefiningInterface was called through all hierarchy recursively while at each level hasProperty called repeatedly which was also traversing whole hierarchy.

I replaced the algorithm by changing the traversal direction and avoided using recursive hasProperty. The new algorithm is also able short circuit when a result is find (versus the old one recursively traversed everything all the time).

This doesn't seem like was taking long in the big picture (only checked stage 1; didn't check effect on disambiguate yet) but I am planning to make hasProperty slightly costlier soon to check parent interfaces so I would like to reduce the likelihood of surprises.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe

Follow aliases and module imports for @define initializers

The criterion for a valid @define initializer is that it be a statically-computable expression containing only literals or other @defines, but existing code used a naïve string-keyed map to determine whether an RHS name was a @define, which fails to understand modules and aliases.

To fix this, we now do an extra pass over all global declarations to find any additional valid aliases, repeating until a fixed point is found.

Also moves isValidDefineValue out of NodeUtil, since this is the only place it should ever be used.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=242953916

Defer declaring goog.requireType imports

Unlike a typical forward reference to a type, which are resolved through NamedType, references to goog.requireType types in goog.modules are currently broken. This is because in cases like

  const Data = goog.requireType('mod.Data');
  let /** !Data */ data;

TypedScopeCreator has already traversed the name "Data" local to the module. Making a NamedType to resolve "Data" is ineffective - we never declare the name "Data" in the module scope.

Two ways of fixing this problem are:
  1) (this CL) visit all goog.requireType imports after all module scopes have been created, but before type resolution.
  2) modify type resolution to make "Data"'s NamedType (and types referencing properties of "Data") resolve in the scope of 'mod.Data', not the current module. This seems more complicated. JSTypeRegistry would have to know that the type name "Data" should actually be resolved in some other scope completely when inside a given module.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=235835564

Remove Es6ExternsCheck

It was only needed to prevent confusing compiler crashes in NTI.  Classic type inference builds the necessary information directly into the type registry so it will not crash.

This should have no visible effect on any existing working builds.  The worst reasonable unintended consequence is either (1) code that was failing with this error will now fail with a compiler crash, or (2) code that was failing with this error will now succeed to compile but produce invalid results.  I do not believe either of these to be remotely likely, but even if it did happen it would not be detectable with a presubmit test, since digging through the already-failing builds is not feasible.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=233452529

BuildGlobalNamespace will not create duplicate Refs

Previously it was up to the caller of scanNewNodes() to avoid passing
BuildGlobalNamespace nodes that might already have references.
This has led to exceptions being thrown because multiple references
were created for the same Node.

This change makes BuildGlobalNamespace and the Name class it depends on smart
enough to avoid creation of additional Refs for the same Node even when
scanNewNodes() is passed AST nodes that already have Refs.

Effectively this means that code modifying the AST can safely pass any Nodes
they think may need reconsideration to the scanNewNodes() method and rely on
BuildGlobalNamespace to do the right thing.

On the other hand, I've added several checks to restrict changing a Ref's Node.

All Refs created by their owning Name

This change enforces that GlobalNamespace.Ref objects will always be created by
the GlobalNamespace.Name object to which they belong.

This allows us to enforce several invariants such as:
* Ref.name will always == the owning Name object
* Ref.node will never be null when initially created except in unit tests
* Ref.scope will never be null except in unit tests

It also allows Name to control the creation of "twin" Refs, which
have several restrictions and are supposed to be the only way for two Refs
to refer to the same Node.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=232698826

Unconditionally extern all symbols used in runtime libraries

Removes the 'declare' pragma that was previously used in global.js, but was implicitly needed by other runtime libraries as well - though this fact was papered over by the Es6ExternsCheck.  Instead, we maintain a list of symbols in VarCheck that will be declared in externs at the end of the pass if they have not been encountered yet.  This is necessary because runtime libraries are injected *after* the first run of VarCheck, so any undeclared (normally externed) symbols in those files will cause undeclared variables that would crash later passes.

This approach is cleaner than conditioanlly declaring the symbols because (a) it avoids duplicate declarations, and (b) it leads to consistent behavior regardless of whether or not certain runtime libraries are included.

This change unblocks removing Es6ExternsCheck, ensuring that the compiler will not crash if no externs are provided.  Type checking runtime libraries without externs is not yet supported.

-------------
Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=232607582

Fix infinite recursion in recursive-typedef subtype check

Recursive typedefs are not supposed to be possible, but there's a way to create them using forward-referenced named types. If such a recursive type is checked against a separate-but-equivalent @record or @typedef type, the type checker currently blows up with infinite recursion. This can be prevented by taking advantage of the ImplCache in PrototypeObjectType#isSubtype.

Doing this correctly requires carefully threading the needle through the various special cases and overrides of isSubtype, particularly due to a separate structural-subtype check that sometimes runs in addition to the version in PrototypeObjectType - if it reports (and caches) a different result then we end up with problems in union coalescing (either under- or over-collapsing), missing property detection, or various other places.
This CL attempts to consolidate the two structural checks into one by adding some extra dimensions to the check: (1) whether the supertype is an inline record literal or not (to determines which properties to match) and (2) whether to require explicitly voidable supertype props to be present in the subtype.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=232525447

Speeds up reading of zip source files

By default zip files created via URL connection supports caching. However this built-in cache never invalidate and we don't want that since zip file contents might change over time.

Earlier attempt to fix this issue killed caching completely which resulted in each individual entry to be independently loaded from the zip archive. That is very inefficient especially for big zip files.

This patch replaces earlier workaround with a timestamp controlled caching so we avoid inefficient re-reads.

With this CL, since it is no longer I/O bounded highly parallel parsing of AST (8+ threads) is 3x faster while the total time of bundling reduced by 40-50% (for J2CL sample app).

The improvement should reflect similarly for other tools (MF, MSS) as well but I didn't measure how much that will be.

The chosen default cache size of 1000 has memory impact around 5MB which is negligible (this is because ZipFile is already designed to be cached indefinitely by JDK since that is default behavior for URLs). Memory testing results/methodology could be found here:
http://[]/experimental/users/goktug/zipstress/Main.java?l=30-35

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=229114925

Improve suspicious code checking of logical operators

Adds a check for the left-hand side of a logical operator having a known value.  It doesn't actually matter which value: if the left-hand side of an AND is always falsy then the right-hand side is dead, and if it's always truthy then its actual value is always discarded anyway.  The only semi-valid usage would be if there were a side effect, and in that case it's still clearer to move the expression to a previous statement, or (if more deeply nested) to use a comma operator.  The rationale for OR is the same, only reversed.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=228231113

Back off less on conditional let/const declarations in LiveVariablesAnalysis

Given a conditionally executed var statement (e.g. for (var x of someArr) {}), it is possible that 'x' was previously assigned to, so 'x' is possibly live prior to the for loop. Normalize does not guarantee that a 'var' is never assigned to before the first 'var' statement.

However, given a conditional let/const declaration, it's safe to say that the variable was 'dead' prior to its declaration because it cannot be assigned referenced in the temporal dead zone.

This improves optimizations during CoalesceVariableNames.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=225557493

Roll RemoveUnusedPolyfills into RemoveUnusedCode

By taking advantage of RemoveUnusedCode's better logic, we are able to do significantly better removal than we could before (in particular, removing the Set polyfill no longer leaves the Map and WeakMap polyfills behind).  This introduces a direct dependency on type information into RemoveUnusedCode where previously it relied entirely on disambiguation for type awareness.  Without type information, polyfills may still be removed, but the accuracy is poorer (unused polyfills may not be removed, and used polyfills that are hidden on aliases may be incorrectly removed).

This CL does not actually switch over to the new logic in DefaultPassConfig yet.  We will do that in a follow-up CL to minimize the size of potentially breaking changes in case of rollbacks.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=221871956

Add a simple polyfill for Math.fround

This polyfill is slightly incorrect for IE8 and IE9, where it performs no rounding at all. This is generally not a problem, since Math.fround is primarily used for optimization (to force faster 32-bit operations rather than 64-bit), but in cases where (a) the logic actually depends on a correct fround implementation and (b) the application targets very old browsers, this polyfill will be insufficient.  For that case, see https://gist.github.com/shicks/7a97ec6b3f10212e60a89a7f6d2d097d for a more correct polyfill that does not depend on Float32Array.

On the other hand, the incorrect (but faster) behavior can be enabled unconditionally for all browsers by setting $jscomp.SIMPLE_FROUND_POLYFILL to true.  This will safe a few bytes and make the operation faster for non-ES6 browsers.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=220720048

Avoid repeating string contents when downleveling tagged template literals.

A tagged template literal has both a raw version and a cooked version. The raw version has not had escape sequences expanded, while a cooked version has. We can save a lot of bytes of output by computing one version from the other. This change implements this optimization for the trivial but common case where the cooked and raw versions of the string are exactly the same.

In a couple of lit-html app that make heavy use of tagged template literals this reduced the js binary size by 1-2% after compression. Before compression the savings are much  larger, 20-25% bytes saved. Turns out compression algorithms are good at compressing long identical strings. I was not able to measure an observable improvement in parse time, any difference in performance (in Chrome at least) was lost in the noise.

Fixes https://github.com/google/closure-compiler/issues/3108

Expand the typechecking of async function declared/inferred return types to allow union types; synthesize a more accurate upper bound for return expression types.

This change is motivated by the case where an async function is inferred to have a union return type (as can happen when one is passed as a callback to some other function that made the type declarations). Since this happens relatively often, and is safe, it was decided to improve checking to support it.

As as consequence, it was also necessary to improve the way we synthesize the return expression type bounds to be more accurately handle "synchronous" types; they can never actually returned. They are now illegal.

-------------
Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=219737644

Fix aliasing of typedefs

Adds a new AST annotation to keep track of any typedef types defined by a definition site. This is different from the type of the value, in that e.g.

```
/** @typedef {string} */
ns.MyString;
```

calling `getJSType()` on the `ns.MyString` qualified name node returns the undefined type, since `ns.MyString` has a runtime value of undefined, but the type *name* represents a string, which we store in `Node#getTypedefTypeProp`. This is necessary so that typedefs can be discovered on aliased namespaces: if `const alias = ns;` then `alias.MyString` will not be in the type registry, but we still need to be able to find it. This is now possible by actually adding the `MyString` property to the namespace type (it was omitted before, defined only in the registry), and then checking the definition node for the new annotation. This annotation is also transferred when a typedef is aliased directly.

This approach is sub-optimal, since it does not consolidate the handling of other kinds of type names, whose types are easily derived from their value types (specifically, constructors and enum objects). It would be nice if typedef objects could also store their typename types, but since most enums are undefined or objects, this would require additional proxying and leads to a mess figuring out where to add the new declarations and not conflict with the subset of typedefs that were already previously being declared. On the other hand, this approach could be consolidated to also include class and enum names, which we may pursue in the future.

Make AggressiveInlineAliases collapse more constructor properties

This change is not a safe optimization, but being slightly unsafe here works around CollapseProperties being unsafe. This relaxes the following condition in AggressiveInlineAliases:
  the pass will inline aliases of a name a.b.c only if the parent names a and a.b are never aliased/escaped

  Now, the pass will also inline aliases of a.b.c /if/ CollapseProperties will (possibly unsafely) collapse "a.b.c" -> "a$b$c", even if a or a.b are still aliased. Note that the InlineTypeAliases pass already inlined "a.b.c" even if "a" or "a.b" escaped, making it less likely that this CL will cause new errors.

This CL also fixes a bug in AggressiveInlineAliases related to nested assigns
  a = b, c = d;
which testing the above change uncovered.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=217632673

Fix bug in AggressiveInlineAliases causing properties to be set to null

This bug was causing bad code to be output by the optimizations. AggressiveInlineAliases would inline constructor properties that also aliased another name, setting the ctor property to null, while there were still indirect references to the ctor property through an alias.

I changed GlobalNamespace to only special case @constructor's when checking 'is this name collapsible', but not when checking 'is this name inlinable?'. Now AggressiveInlineAliases will wait to set a constructor property to null until the constructor is never escaped/aliased.

This CL contains branching logic to minimize the change to InlineAliases (a.k.a. InlineTypeAliases), because changing that pass causes new type errors. We can remove the logic after the typechecker handles nullability of aliased enums/typedef correctly.

*** Reason for rollback ***

Rollforward and fixing original issue that caused the rollback.

The fix includes:
- During code generation, instead of just using the raw string when generating template literals, use function escapeUnrecognizedCharacters to escape characters that might be misinterpreted later on. However, for characters such as \n and \u2028 we still use the actual raw character as is.

*** Original change description ***

Allow invalid escape sequences in tagged template literals.

The "raw" property on template literal substrings is always set as the string exactly as typed in input, but if the escape sequence is invalid, the "cooked" value of the template literal would be undefined.

Also update tranpilation of template literals to reflect the change.

Update the code generator to always use raw strings in template literals.

As part of the fix, change TemplateLit nodes to have TemplateLiteralSubstringNode children rather than String children, and updated affected files to reflect the change.

jQuery.prototype.attr

According to the documentation ( https://api.jquery.com/attr/#attr2 )
Since at least jQuery 1.6:
If arg1 is a string, arg2 is "String or Number or Null"
If arg1 is an object, arg2 is "Function( Integer index, String attr ) => String or Number" and "this is the current element"

- Improved first parameter object definition
- Second parameter can't be a boolean
- Improved second parameters function prototype

Closes https://github.com/google/closure-compiler/pull/3094.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=215492900

Allow invalid escape sequences in tagged template literals.

The "raw" property on template literal substrings is always set as the string exactly as typed in input, but if the escape sequence is invalid, the "cooked" value of the template literal would be undefined.

Also update tranpilation of template literals to reflect the change.

Update the code generator to always use raw strings in template literals.

As part of the fix, change TemplateLit nodes to have TemplateLiteralSubstringNode children rather than String children, and updated affected files to reflect the change.

For example, foo`a${b}c` would create a tree
TAGGED_TEMPLATELIT
    NAME foo
        TEMPLATELIT
            TEMPLATELIT_STRING a
            TEMPLATELIT_SUB
                NAME b
            TEMPLATELIT_STRING c

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=213481890

Conformance checks: handle unions containing unknown types.

During type checking, unions containing the unknown type are collapsed into just the unknown type. These then get flagged as "not an explicitly declared unknown type", because while the type is just the unknown type, its declaration is still found to be a union of something.

This change explicitly handles unions containing unknown types by checking if any member is unknown, and allowing that pattern. It also adds a test checking for the parse of unknown|? and null|? types.

Do not remove empty files in ConvertToTypedInterface pass.

Currently, passing an empty file into ConvertToTypedInterface within a test results in a "deleted scope was not reported" crash, because the deletion is reported to the deleted node itself, not the parent. It doesn't seem to be possible to report to the parent (the root) because it is neither a script nor a function. Therefore I'm removing the code that deletes empty files.

One test has to change because the synthetic "fill files" created by the compiler to populate otherwise empty chunks are now visible in the IJS output. We might want to figure out a way to get rid of them in the future.

Since `modules` is initialized to the same value that gets passed into the `JSModuleGraph` constructor, we can replace any reference to the former by a call to `moduleGraph.getModules()` (which now returns an iterable, rather than a list).

Some care must be taken on `restoreState`, which needs to update the names of the deserialized modules to match the preexisting ones. To avoid concurrent modification, a copy of the previous module list must be made.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=211438141

Remove the Compiler `inputs` member variable.

The `inputs`, `modules` and `moduleGraph` compiler data structures overlap, which violates the SPOT rule and makes maintenance of the compiler's internal state more error-prone. This CL remedies part of the problem by removing `inputs` in favor of a `JSModuleGraph#getAllInputs` method, which returns an iterable over inputs in dependency order.

Note that it's already the case that `inputs` is in dependency order, since `initModules` and `rebuildInputsFromModules` (two of the three places where `inputs` is set, the third being `restoreState`) already initialize it in that manner. Thus, in most places where `inputs` occurs, we can simply replace it by a `moduleGraph.getAllInputs()` call. The exceptions are the methods that mutate the module graph: `hoistExterns` and `hoistNoCompileFiles`. In both cases, iteration must be over a copy of `getAllInputs()` to prevent concurrent modification.

Also note that, in `orderInputs`, passing `inputs` as an argument into `JSModuleGraph#manageDependencies` is redundant, since the graph itself contains that information.

Finally, a couple of places verify that the compiler has been initialized by a null check on `inputs`. These must be replaced by a null check on `moduleGraph`.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=209619585

For types defined using CLASS, use the MEMBER_FUNCTION_DEF of "constructor", rather than the CLASS node, as the definition node of the type's "constructor" property.

This change makes it possible to lookup JSDoc attached to the CLASS and "constructor" separately. Such distinction is a prerequisite for separate handling for class/constructor access-controls.

Additionally, literal accesses to "constructor" properties (e.g. `Foo.prototype.constructor`, `foo.constructor`) will become subject to access controls following this change. Previously, they had been subject to the same controls as the class itself by dint of using the same JSDoc.

Fixes some violations of the `equals-hashCode` contract in `NamedType`.

`NamedType` instances used to only be compared based on their string references. Now, if they have been successfully resolved they will be compared based on their underlying (proxied) type instances, else fall back to comparing strings.

This change is not a complete fix because:
  - `NamedType` equality should also consider scopes
  - There is some ambiguity between forward declared types and `NoResolvedType` I haven't been able to unravel.
Fixing these has been punted in favour of an incremental improvement.

As a confirmation that this change is positive and to help prevent the contract from slipping further, `assertTypeEquals` in the "jstype" unit tests is being updated to compare `hashCode()` in addition to `equals()`.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=207634784

Refactors `CheckAccessControls` to work with an abstraction of a "property reference" rather than a GETROP node directly.

This change is a step towards adding support for ES6 class syntax. It is necessary because class syntax creates new ways of referencing properties that the existing code didn't model well. Refactoring to this abstraction allows us to reuse the existing logic, which is large, complex, and fragile.

A number of latent errors in access control checking were discovered during this change (unchecked l-value syntaxes, ambiguity between override/overload/access). These issues are left as is since this is intended to have minimal impact on behaviour. Fixes will come later.

A bunch of code is forked from `AccessControlUtils` into `CheckAccessControls` to support the new abstraction. A tracking bug exists for reconciliation.

Handle new Polymer 3 import styles for PolymerElement and the Polymer function in the Closure PolymerPass.

Polymer 3 uses ES modules instead of globals. This updates the PolymerPass to recognize identifiers associated with ES module imports (which when the PolymerPass runs are GETPROPs instead of flat NAMEs).

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=204775979

Type check uses of `super` correctly in static methods

This initial support uses a partial, hacky workaround in order to exactly reproduce the same warnings as type checking pre-transpiled code.  A more correct implementation would be based on the type of `this` in the static method, but currently `this` in static methods are treated as unknown, so tightening that would introduce many new errors across the codebase, which would block moving class transpilation to after type checking.  Instead, we will tighten the types in a later step.

This is the last known blocker for type checking classes natively.  Once this is in, we should be able to move class transpilation to after type checking.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=204554183

Allow duplicate @suppress tags by collecting the union of suppressions.

This makes it much easier for automated tools to add to the list of suppressions for a file without having to parse and merge JSDoc, just by appending to an existing @fileoverview comment.

This reduces errors reported from human authored code, but it seems unlikely that a duplicate @suppress tag is an actual mistake – human authored code usually has all suppress tags in the same line in a short comment, so it seems unlikely that anybody would accidentally add a dupe. On top of that, it seems fairly clear that taking the union of suppressions is the intended behaviour when having multiple @suppress tags.

Enhance scope class in SymbolTable to contain its index in parent scope.

This is needed to generate unique names for variables. Today we achieve that by treating each block scope as an anonymous function scope and generating "function%n" symbol for all block scopes. That leads to a lot of unnecessary symbols which are "not clickable" and generally misleading.

Fix NodeTraversal#traverseAtScope and use it in TypedScopeCreator

This fixes the issue of traversing extends nodes multiple times, without needing any special casing.  Previously traverseAtScope did not handle class roots very well, and was somewhat inconsistent with its handling of function name nodes. Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=203143845

Allow accessing undeclared variables using `typeof SomeVar`.

`typeof x === 'undefined'` is the strict mode compliant way to check if a
variable.

Users should ideally declare externs for variables, but this isn't possible for
TypeScript. TypeScript emits code snippets under certain situations that check
for the presence of a variable and use it if it is defined. We could suppress
`checkVars` in the emit, but we'd rather not, given the check is valuable.

Accepting use within an explicit `typeof` check seems unlikely to permit genuine
errors, and likely to just match explicit checks by users.

Resolve function templates within the function body

Rather than storing temporary state in the registry, this state is now moved out into a temporary StaticTypedScope implementation.  It does still require some special handling to look for names in this special type of scope, but the lifetime of this overlay is now much cleaner.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=200745756

Synchronize access points to SourceMap.addSourceFile.

Multiple threads parsing source files may discover inline source maps and add
their contents to the compiler's source map concurrently. SourceMap itself is
non-threadsafe. While `sourceMapOriginalSources` and `inputSourceMaps` use a
concurrent hash map, concurrent access to the source map itself must be guarded
by synchronizing on the Compiler object, which this change does by synchronizing
`Compiler.addFilesToSourceMap` and `Compiler.addSourceMapSourceFiles` (the two
methods accessing sources content on the source map).

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=200717495

Update `hashCode()` on `TemplatizedType` to be equal to that of the corresponding `IntanceObjectType` when all template parameter values are the unknown type. (i.e. `hashCode(Foo) == hashCode(Foo<?>)`)

This is being done because currently such pairs of types (a raw template type and it's specialization on unknown) are considered identity equal (`equals()`). Therefore, the old behaviour violated the contract of `hashCode()`.

In a better world we would rather have `Foo !== Foo<?>`, but that change has larger implications. This CL represents a quick fix to bring things to a less-bad state.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=199163871

Consolidate TypedScopeCreator's ScopeBuilders

LocalScopeBuilder and GlobalScopeBuilder were basically doing the same thing, with the only difference being how function scopes were handled.  With ES6 block scoping, function scopes are much more limited: they never include any statements and therefore don't have any declarations.  This change combines the existing two concrete ScopeBuilder subclasses into a NormalScopeBuilder, but pulls out the separate behavior for FunctionScopeBuilder into its own place, differentiated by completely different shouldTraverse() and visit() logic.

It turns out that much of the complex type creation logic is actually still needed in both, since blockless arrow functions and default parameter initializers still allow object literals to exist directly in function scopes - so parsing JSDoc function declarations (etc) is still required.  But we can get by with less branching and special casing in shouldTraverse, and this opens the door to a separate ClassScopeBuilder in the near future with its own separate logic.

MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=196883605

Complete rewrite of LinkedFlowScope to use PersistentMap.

The new version is comparable in overall performance (inferSlotType() is about 3x slower, but getSlot(), equals(), and JoinOp are all about 3x faster), but is much cleaner and easier to reason about.  There is no longer a separate cache, so there's no longer any need for duplicated logic between the linked list and the cache.  Moreover, with the nested maps, it's now trivial to remove inner block scopes when they are exited, or qualified names when their receivers should be invalidated (see #2854).

Closes github.com/google/closure-compiler/issues/2904.

See github.com/google/closure-compiler/issues/2904

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=196258353

Enable CommonJS name mangling in for loop initializers containing multiple variable declarations.

Previously compiling a loop like:
for(var i = 0, n = 5; i < n; i++) {}
resulted in mangling of variable references, but not the declarations:
for(var i = 0, n = 5; i$$test < n$$test; i$$test++) {}

This happened, because name mangler skipped multi-variable declarations under assumptions that they would be split into separate statements per variable. At the same time, the code splitting the declarations bailed on for loop initializers (because there can be only one initializer statement).

The offending code was added in https://github.com/google/closure-compiler/commit/71b36e83b928ce63fa66f727f744ff2aefbe647c and https://github.com/google/closure-compiler/commit/6f43ec65e570b983a46bc7a652e42f89f1f92e67.

Why we need two splitMultipleDeclarations (in updateNameReference as well as in RewriteModule.visit) is beyond me. I suspect that this code is still not 100% correct, but better than before.

Closes https://github.com/google/closure-compiler/issues/2918.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=194030432

Add parentheses around "{" at the start of an arrow function body

We already had logic to add parentheses when the object literal was the only thing being returned, but not when the object literal or object pattern was more deeply nested in an expression.

To do this I added two states to the CodeGenerator.Context enum. One is for when we are at the start of an arrow function body and the other is for the case where we are both in an arrow function body and inside a for loop init clause.

(Deciding to add parentheses by recursing to see the leftmost child is an object lit caused some unnecessary parentheses: e.g. in cases where something like a cast also added parentheses before the "{", I was adding parentheses twice)

Fixes https://github.com/google/closure-compiler/issues/2883

Refactor CompilerTypeTestCase to fix a problem with TypeCheckTest

need most of the definitions they contain.

Prepare TypedScopeCreator to work with ES6 block scopes.

1. Split the `scope` field in TypedScopeCreator.AbstractScopeBuilder into `currentScope` and `currentHoistScope`.  These currently point to the same object, so no behavior change is expected.

Clean up LinkedFlowScope a bit.

* Remove unnecessary calls to LinkedFlowScope#optimize.  When checking equivalence, it's not necessary to walk up both scopes' parent chains.  All that matters is that the the lastSlot is the same - this check is now implemented in LinkedFlowScope#optimizesToSameScope.

* Add FlowScope#getDeclarationScope and use it in TypeInference, rather than just using the stored function scope directly.  Currently these are the same scope, but once block scopes are introduced, it will be relevant.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=189382326

Streamline special handling in Var.Arguments to also handle 'this' and 'super'.

Adds an AbstractScope.ImplicitVar enum that includes the three special vars that are implicitly created in different scopes.  The enum provides a method to know whether any given scope creates the var, and is integrated into the various Scope.getVar() methods to do the right thing.

This is a step toward supporting ES6 block scopes in LinkedFlowScope, since we need to be more careful exactly which scope to declare qualified names on (there's no longer just the function scope, but the various block scopes in between).  The general approach is to look for the root of the qualified name and this streamlines the case where the root is 'this' or 'super' to not need any special handling.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=187348592

Extract ScopedName as an abstract superclass of AbstractVar.

Background: CL 181680335 fixed/generalized the equals and hashCode behavior of Var and TypedVar, which previously only depended on the definition node, to instead depend on the name and the root node of the scope in which the name was defined.  Importantly, this preserved the property that Vars needn't share the same scope creator to be equal, but was still required to be an instance of AbstractVar, which requires a corresponding AbstractScope.  This CL loosens that requirement, in particular by providing a simple value type `ScopedName.of(name, node)` which can be used alongside (e.g.) TypedVar as keys in the same ScopedName-keyed map.  This is a step toward supporting block scopes in OTI (#2796).

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=187266949

Roll memoization directly into TypedScopeCreator.

This is a prerequisite for handling block scoping correctly: to ensure names are defined in the correct order, TypedScopeCreator needs to create nested block scopes when they are encountered in the createScope traversal, rather than afterwards.  This is required for, e.g. `if (true) { class Base {} } class Sub extends Base {}`.  TypedScopeCreator can now create these scopes and be sure they are correctly memoized.  This is straightforward since every usage of TypedScopeCreator was always wrapped in MemoizedTypedScopeCreator.  The upshot is that MemoizedTypedScopeCreator can now be deleted.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=184010090

Introduce optional strict property checks.

Add the "strictMissingProperties" diagnostic group.  While the current "missingProperties" warnings report when a property can't be found on the type or any of its subtypes, when the "strictMissingProperties" diagnostic group is enabled, the type check will report references to properties that are not declared on that type.

As the subtype property references are typed as "unknown" this encourages patterns that less frequently into pits of cascading unknowns.

The historic "missingProperties" check was implemented they way it was in no small part because of the awkwardness of typing the DOM API (knowning which subclass of Node/Element you are expecting, etc) and it is expected that this will continue to be the case here that it is awkward.

Also here, we hack the suppression guard so that "checkTypes" and "missingProperties" include the "strictMissingProperties" warnings when they are used for suppressions.

Note this CL lays a solid foundation for these checks but there are two areas of follow up:
property assignments and properties of unions types require additional unit tests.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=181748544

Make TypedScope no longer extend Scope and TypedVar no longer extend Var.

These two changes need to be done simultaneously since TypedScopes want to return TypedVars and vice versa, and if one subclass relationship is broken then the return types of the other are no longer properly covariant.

Making the typed and untyped versions of Scope and Var more distinct allows using generics more cleanly.  It also enables us to remove the redundant overrides in the typed versions that simply called the superclass and casted the result.  Many of those methods in the abstract base class can now be marked 'final'.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=181681216

Fix equals and hashCode methods for Var and TypedVar.

Previously they were keyed off of nameNode, but this has two problems: (1) nameNode can be null, such as in TypedScopeCreator#declareNativeType, or in many unit tests - in this case hashCode would throw; (2) nameNode is not always unique for different variables (particularly qualified names).  Additionally, TypedVar did not satisfy the equals contract since Var.equals(TypedVar) could return true while TypedVar.equals(Var) would return false.

The new approach is to compare the variable's name and its scope's root node.  Both of these things should never be null, and together they actually *do* uniquely identify the variable.  We no longer distinguish between Var and TypedVar: they can now freely equal each other if they refer to the same symbol in the code.

This allows all var instances to be used safely as map keys (rather than just some), which is important for teaching the type checker about ES6 scopes.  Control flow graphs are necessarily at function granularity, rather than block, so with ES6 scoping variable names alone are no longer sufficient to track the flow of data through different blocks.

Note that identity semantics is incorrect here since vars can be stored and compared across traversals (i.e. different scopes).  This also has the benefit of allowing to remove some of the special (and less correct) handling for arguments variables.

The old interface had broken generics, since it required any given ScopeCreator implementation to be able to create any type of scope subclass. Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=180681077

Detect Feature.BLOCK_SCOPED_FUNCTION_DECLARATIONS correctly and set it as an ES6 feature.

This change has two main consequences:
1. Some code that was previously considered to be ES5 will now be marked as ES6, resulting in transpilation occurring in test runners, bundlers, and debug loaders.  If LANGUAGE_IN is explicitly set to ES5, or if ES6 externs are missing, it's possible that builds could break.
2. A possible behavior change for ambiguous block-scoped declarations.  The code `function f(){return 1;} {function f(){return 2;}} console.log(f());` will print '2' in sloppy mode, but '1' in ES6 strict mode (and is an error in ES5 strict mode).  Depending on a variety of other factors, the compiler may output ES5 code printing either result; this change will make it always obey the strict-mode behavior and print '1'.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=179954526

Don't collapse type unions of non-declared symbols in partial mode.

Previously:
/** @type {Foo|Bar} */
const variable;

in partial mode where Foo and Bar weren't defined, resulted in variable having the type (Foo|null).  In partial mode, both Foo and Bar are part of the type and should be kept around.  See https://github.com/angular/clutz/issues/625.

This CL fixes this by changing how Named, NoResolved Types are compared.  Instead of having all NoResolvedTypes be equivalent, Named, NoResolved Types are equivalent if their reference names are the same.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=179502397

Roll forward 179255046: Normalize shorthand object properties.

NEW: updated transpile.js to be in sync with the final state of the CL, rather than an intermediate state.

Automated g4 rollback of changelist 179430808.

*** Reason for rollback ***

Roll forward

*** Original change description ***

Automated g4 rollback of changelist 179255046.

*** Reason for rollback ***

Breaks transpilation.

*** Original change description ***

Normalize shorthand object properties.

After this change, the AST no longer has special forms for shorthand object properties (i.e. {x}), neither in object literals nor in object destructuring patterns.  Import specs are unchanged.

All handling of shorthand properties has been pushed to the extremities of parsing (which returns the same AST as {x:x}, except the STRING_KEY node has an IS_SHORTHAND_PROPERTY annotation) and code generation (which will re-collapse the property if the annotation is present and the names are the same).

This greatly simplifies a number of checks, transpilations, and optimizations, which now no longer need to deal with a different form of tree.

***

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=177275858

Fix NTI Java types to adhere to contract of equals().

The contract indirectly requires that equals() must never throw, due to symmetry: if someRandomObject.equals(someFunctionType) returns false, then someFunctionType.equals(someRandomObject) must also return false, rather than throwing an IllegalArgumentException.  A number of NTI data types violated this contract, which can cause very confusing problems.

Effective Java Item #8 discusses this at great length.

Improve the compile time cost for Optimize Calls from #1 to #17 (roughly 25% of its previous time).

Instead of using the DefinitionUseSiteFinder, as simpler data structure is introduced: OptimizeCalls.ReferenceMap.  The ReferenceMap provides a simple list of nodes for every global name and property. This avoids building objects and structures, and identifiers that are unneeded, and avoided redundant analysis.

***

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=173304853

[NTI] Change the subtyping rule for the receiver type of functions.

For method overrides, make it stricter (to catch the same warnings as OTI). We were ignoring @this completely before and now we don't.

For other function subtyping, make it looser. The motivation here is to avoid spurious warnings when dubious overrides (such as toString) need to be checked during structural subtyping. See the new test with IObject.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=172940208

[NTI] Add an "unresolved type" to the type system.

This type is useful for per-library type checking. The semantics is that this type is neither a subtype nor a supertype of any other type. In effect, if you try to use it, you get a warning.

To avoid flowing this type around and having to change all type operations to recognize it, if an expression evaluates to this type, we warn and return ? instead.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=168885731

Define "crypto" as a global variable.

Crypto is available on Window (or the global object for workers). Closure understands that global variables are also available on the window object, but not the other way around. Additionally, these were incorrectly defined on "Window.prototype".

With this change, Closure code can use both "window.crypto" and "crypto" to refer to the object, not just "window.crypto" as previously.

See also
https://github.com/google/closure-compiler/blob/master/src/com/google/javascript/jscomp/DeclaredGlobalExternsOnWindow.java

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=168061516

Fix problems with export and function/class declarations.

This stops Normalize from splitting export default + a function/class declarations with since default exports are unnamed.

It also stops rewriting of
  export function foo() {}
to
  export var foo = function() {];
as foo is block-scoped and hoisted (so https://github.com/google/closure-compiler/pull/429 does not apply).

Also changes the behavior of some NodeUtil helpers and unit tests to acknowledge that export default can contain module-level function and class declarations, which is both technically correct and should aid future work on export statements. For example, this creates a function foo in the module scope:
  export default function foo() {};

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=168025536

Call assertAbout() instead of directly calling Subject constructors.
Direct calls require access to a FailureStrategy instance, and we're hiding those instances.

Additionally, in this particular CL, call check().about(...) instead of directly calling a Subject constructor with THROW_ASSERTION_ERROR.
Avoiding the Subject constructor is good for the reasons described above. But switching specifically to check().about(...) rather than assertAbout(...) also means that, if someone uses the Subject with a different failure strategy, we'll correctly propagate that strategy to derived subjects, rather than switch back to THROW_ASSERTION_ERROR.

I know that this CL adds a lot of boilerplate. If it's any consolation:
- We plan for check() to automatically add context in the future, so you'll get some value from it.
- We plan to convert SubjectFactory to an interface, so we'll come back and convert these all to "public static SubjectFactory<FooSubject> foos() { return FooSubject::new; }."

Sorry for the mess in the meantime.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=166652159

Prevent calls to getLastCompiler() from TypeICompilerTestCase.

When TypeInferenceMode is BOTH, this call is practically guaranteed to be an error.  The entire purpose is to do some additional check on the AST or some other aspect of the compile, but in BOTH mode, there are two different compilers created, and only the second one (NTI) is accessible afterwards.

The fix is to add a new Postcondition TestPart to CompilerTestCase, which contains a callback that accepts the Compiler and is called at the end of CompilerTestCase#testInternal, so that all test cases can be verified separately.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=166543544

Move J2CLConstantHoisterPass out of j2clOptBundle.

Currently when constant hoister bundled together with other passes, the changes made in that pass are not visible to Clinit passes until the another run of the pass (since they only look at what is provided in changedScope).

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=166413679

Removes clinits more aggressively in J2clClinitPrunerPass.

When there is a deep class hierarchy, even the clinits are empty, we can only remove one clinit at each pass.
This makes the number of optimization loops to be at least same as the level of depth of class hierarchy and each loop is quite expensive since a lot of passes not looking at only changed code.

This patch updates clinit pruning pass to be more aggressive and remove clinits/references to a fixed-point in single pass. As a result we can remove  whole empty chain in the class hierarchy in single pass instead of relying on other passess to cleanup to be able to do more removals.

This CL drops number of runs in gmail by 11 and reduces the stage 2 total time by 10%

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=160464984

Use the span of the function name for method defs in object literals and goog.defineClass.

For object literals:
Previously we used the span of the entire function for the STRING_KEY for a
function's name when it was a method def in an object literal. For example, in
'var foo = { f2() {}};', the span for f2 would be 'f2() {}'. With this change,
the span for the name will just be 'f2'.

For goog.defineClass:
We would use the root of the property as the truth for
source location information during the rewrite of the property name. When you
used foo: function()... syntax, this would work because the root is a STRING_KEY
for foo. However, if you used foo() {} syntax the root would still be the
MEMBER_FUNCTION_DEF, which has a span covering the whole function. In the
MEMBER_FUNCTION_DEF case, we actually want to use the first-first child (a NAME
node) for the source location information.

[NTI] Implement JSType#getSubTypes

Includes some minor changes to the semantics.  In particular, there's no reason to keep a class' subtypes separate form an interface's direct implementors: NTI does not make this distinction, and no callers distinguish (rather, they just end up asking for both).  So #getDirectImplementors has been folded into #getSubTypes.  Additionally, it no longer ever returns null: an empty list is returned instead, making it more ergonomic to use.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=159255956

RefasterJS templates for replacing the usage of Array.prototype.indexOf to determine whether an element is in the array or not with Array.prototype.includes.

This refactoring covers the most common cases in which this can be expressed:

'arr.includes(elem)' is equivalent to:
  - arr.indexOf(elem) != -1
  - arr.indexOf(elem) !== -1
  - arr.indexOf(elem) > -1
  - arr.indexOf(elem) >= 0

'!arr.includes(elem)' is equivalent to:
 - arr.indexOf(elem) == -1
 - arr.indexOf(elem) === -1
 - arr.indexOf(elem) < 0

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=158794884

[NTI] Fix lint errors in NewTypeInference and JSTypes.

Many of the errors were about constant-named fields that aren't actually constant.  I opted to just suppress these warnings, rather than rename them, since they do behave like constants, and they should be consistent across different files.

It might be nice to fix these someday down the road, though it's not clear what the best approach would be.  Simply adding "commonTypes." isn't too terrible, particularly for any that are only used once or twice; for more frequently-used types, a getter and/or query method might be more appropriate.

Alternatively, if we could (a) eliminate the `inCompatibilityMode` flag to JSTypes, and (b) make the rest of the fields constant, it would be possible to make these types actually static constants.  The second part might be difficult, since the properties of many of these types *do* depend on externs, which may change from compilation to compilation.  These would take a lot more work to factor out: we'd need to figure out how to remove the reference to JSTypes in the really-constant versions, or else have an extra instance of it with only a subset of types (provided this doesn't cause any problems).

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=157742578

Backoff of nested functions in the CheckMissingSuper pass.

It's acceptable to reference 'this' from within a function that is within an ES6 constructor before calling the super(). It will only be a runtime error if the function is called before the super() has returned. However, the JS cannot prove this, nor can it prove that 'this' is not bound to something entirely different. Therefore it should backoff in these cases.

This also uncovered a bug where the pass would accept the super() call from a nested class as the super() call for the enclosing class, this has also been fixed.

[NTI] Migrate TypedCodePrinter to NTI.

In performing this migration, a number of bugs on OTI's typed code printing surfaced (primarily around nullability), so I fixed them and added a few regression tests.

One omission was leaving out the `@this` annotation from functions.  Fixing this unfortunately introduces a few redundant `@this` annotations where they shouldn't be necessary (we currently do a bit of work to try to eliminate these, but it depends on type information in the AST which isn't always available - see a few test cases that have been changed; potentially it's not worth doing this at all and we could eliminate the extra logic and simply always emit `@this`).

A number of new TypeI methods were required to support this.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe

[NTI] Add a ToStringContext for adapting how JSTypes are stringified.

This addresses two problems at once:
1. Issue #2499 where type variables are ambiguated, making warnings difficult to understand
2. Migrating `TypedCodeGenerator` to NTI requires printing types in a "for annotations" mode

Rather than add various booleans, the context object allows plumbing any configuration all the way through the recursive stringify operation, and is extensible if further configuration is needed later.  Moreover, context instances may be passed to multiple stringify operations (i.e. to ensure typevars are printed consistently throughout an entire message).

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=156454716

Instanceof guards should not block code motion.

This change fixes a bug in CrossModuleCodeMotion that could potentially have a
big impact on how code is moved across modules.

When a reference looks like this
`x instanceof Foo`

CrossModuleCodeMotion changes it to this:
`'undefined' != typeof Foo && x instanceof Foo`

Once that is done, it is safe to ignore the reference when deciding where to
move Foo.

This change is to ensure that CrossModuleCodeMotion
ignores the added `'undefined' != typeof Foo` references when it is run
repeatedly.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=156103437

Fix ranges for exported variables

Previously, ranges for all nodes under an exported variable were that of the parent node of the original variable. So code like:

"""
const FOO = "text";

exports = { FOO: FOO}
"""

would result in the FOO node (and all sub nodes including the STRING node) having a range the encompassed the entire line. This causes problems for programs that rely on the ranges for these variables.

Just use "stage1" and "stage2" to refer to the primary compilation stages.

Also remove deprecations I previously put in place on compile()
and compileModules().

It's become clear that we need the flexibility of deciding within the compiler
whether a given transpilation pass will occur before or after a given
optimization pass. We won't be explicitly having a 'transpilation' phase.

Stage 1 represents all checks and whatever transpilation has to happen in order
for the checks to work.
Stage 2 represents all optimizations and whatever transpilation has to happen
there.

Introduces --remove_j2cl_asserts flag similar to --remove_closure_asserts flag.

This simplifies preserving the java semantic of removing side effects without requiring special code generation at all call sides.
As a plus this makes it more readable, less prone to optimization orders and follows java closer (ie. byte code always contains asserts while the JVM strips them away).

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=154990784

Fixes a "reported changes must have a scope" violation in OptimizeParameters.

It relies on a definition finder instance as an index within which to find
parameters to change/remove. But it was not updating the index to match
ongoing AST changes which sometimes lead to the index containing references
to already-removed nodes and this lead the duplicative attempts to remove
them and report the associated change.

The pass was making a cursory attempt to mitigate this by collecting all the
removed nodes into a list and then updating the index at the end, but it was
possible for the duplicate removal attempts to occur between the original
removal and before the late index update.

I changed the index updates to each occur immediately after each node
removal.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=154919812

Fixes a "reported changes must have a scope" violation in RemoveUnusedVars.

RemoveUnusedVars was sometimes removing references inside of subtrees that
were already removed. Correct this in an elegant way is very difficult
because the different removals are tracked in different datastructures,
some of which are difficult to update for nodes in subtress and others of
which don't track the full set of node types.

I had a larger, less hacky and slower solution. But it didn't always work
since defFinder doesn't track GET_ELEM nodes and the other tracking
datastructures do.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe

Refactor AST change tracking to correct inaccuracies introduced when SCRIPT became a change scope root.  SCRIPT nodes were not being set as the "change scope" when a function scope was pop'd from the scope stack if there was not a block scope between the script and the function.  Script nodes are only on the scope stack during some unit tests, when the traversal is started from a SCRIPT rather than a ROOT, during normal operation SCRIPT are not semantic scope roots.

Disable a few tests that no longer pass with these changes.

Also introduce an alternate version that doesn't depend on compiler state in "NodeTraversal#reportCodeChange" that can be used by passes that can be run in multiple threads at the same time.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=152771274

Per-scope change detection validation in the unit tests is broken (the older
all or nothing validation works correctly). Several issues:
* There was a logic mismatch with regard to which Nodes should be checked and
SCRIPT nodes were being ignored.
* The validation was only run if the PhaseOptimizer set but CompilerTestCase
does use PhaseOptimizer by default (some all but a few don't)
* The validation was comparing the state before the setup passes ran (es6
transpilation, normalization, etc) so a unit test might pass even if it didn't
mark a pass as changed.
* The validate logic, in unit tests, was not checking scopes not marked as changed but only
 validated that marked nodes had been changed (the latter is less likely to be
 incorrect).
* The validation logic was ignoring Node annotations when comparing node for
changes which causes some false negative results.

In addition to the validation logic fixes, this simplifies the Compiler/PhaseOptimizer interaction with regard to change tracking and makes way for future changes.

The validation is now turned off by default.  The next
change will turn it on by default with appropriate fixes.

Moves all input IO into a dedicated pass for better time measurement.

Previously IO and parsing occurred in the same pass which made it hard to
know if performance fluctuation was caused by CPU contention or IO
contention. After this change it should be possible to know if IO
performance is the culprit.

Tracer mode now looks like:
Log:
pass,runtime,allocMem,codeChanged,astReduction,reduction,gzReduction,astSize,size,gzSize
readInputs,319,42,false,0,0,0,0,0,0
parseInputs,3851,88,false,0,0,0,0,0,0
beforeStandardChecks,1,119,false,0,0,0,0,0,0
checkJsDoc,307,119,false,0,0,0,0,0,0
...

We now recognize feature detection, such as `if (x.repeat) x.repeat(42);` and don't inject the String.prototype.repeat polyfill in cases where the code won't crash if it's not present. Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=141211968

Improve ArrowType.hashCode and FunctionType.hashCode to make hash collisions less likely.

For ArrowType:
The previous version simply summed all the parameter hashcodes, but since + is commutative this means that function(a,b){} and function(b,a){} would have the same hashCode.

Also it included the 'returnTypeInferred' field in the hashCode though it was not part of equals().  This has been fixed.

For FunctionType:
All functions with the same ArrowType would get the same hashcode.  To resolve this we instead just hash more data.

Doing this revealed a bug in the equals() method for FunctionType where it was assymmetric and allowed constructors to be equal to ordinary functions in some circumstances.  This has been also been fixed.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=139516879

Improve the performance of Node.getQualifiedName

The way this was implemented recursively it would cause one StringBuilder to
be instantiated for each level of a qualified name so

a.b.c.d

would allocate 3 StringBuilders and the string 'a' would get copied 6 times.
(once into the string builder and once calling toString on the builder) With
this change we will allocate exactly one StringBuilder and copy 'a' exactly 2
times (no matter how many levels of qualification there are).  This should be
faster and produce much less garbage.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=136085292

Extracts aggressive alias inlining out of CollapseProperties, now it's own pass.

This is good both because it makes CollapseProperties more focused and because
it makes the aggressively inlined AST state available to other optimization
passes that want to be able to assume such an AST state as input.

In the past some passes (like J2clPropertyInliner) assumed that aliases would be
inlined before they saw the AST, and when this was not true the solution was to
tell users that it was their responsibility to mark type alias vars @const so
that the InlineAliases pass would handle them. But it is no longer the desire of
JSCompiler team to require this of users, which makes the change (being performed
in this CL) a necessity.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=135297871

Make GeolocationPositionOptions a @record

As a @constructor, user code which calls Geolocation methods generates a warning. Since there is no user-callable constructor, this needs to be a @record in order to allow an Object with the given properties to be treated as valid.

Additionally, the three properties are supposed to be optional, so their types now allow undefined. (Should they allow null too?)
From the spec (https://dev.w3.org/geo/api/spec-source.html#position_options_interface):

> In ECMAScript, the enableHighAccuracy, timeout and maximumAge properties are all optional: when creating a PositionOptions object, the developer may specify any of these properties.

Also made position of type annotations consistent (on request).

Closes https://github.com/google/closure-compiler/pull/2063

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=134015827

Automated g4 rollback of changelist 133907989.

*** Reason for rollback ***

Looks to break many projects that don't @export their enums properly.  They should be fixed before rolling forward.

*** Original change description ***

Fix enum type references in generated externs

When a generated extern referenced an enum type in a parameter or
record type, the primitive underlying the enum was being used instead
of the enum itself.  For example, this code:

  /** @enum {number} */
  var E = { A: 1, B: 2 };
  /**
   * @param {function(E)} takesEnum
   * @param {E} e
   */
  function f(takesEnum, e) {
    takesEnum(e);
  }

Would become this in the generated externs for the library:

  /** @enum {number} */
  var E = { A: 1,...

***

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=131654877

Allow applying input source maps to the generated source map.

This allows users to easily map from generated source that's an
input to the compiler back into their original source files.

E.g. when compiling TypeScript, users would have:
    input.ts -(a)-> input.js -(b)-> compiled.js

Where (a) is the TypeScript compilation operation, and (b) is Closure
Compiler. With this option set, the source map generated in (a) is
applied to the operation (b), with the final source map mapping back
into `input.ts` from locations in `compiled.js`.

This also introduces an interface `SourceFileMapping` to avoid
increasing the coupling and responsibility of the Compiler object.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=131624213

Avoid some TemplateTypeMap duplication during subtype checking.

This reduces 'checkTypes' time in the J2CL 'timing' readable example
(which uses Guava) from 24.5 seconds to 1.7 seconds.

For future reference, note that when performing subtype analysis
JSCompiler sometimes incidentally calls
TemplateTypeMap.getResolvedTemplateType(). With that out of the way we
continue:

It just so happens that the TemplateTypeMap datastructure allows its
contained list of template keys and the list of template values to
have different lengths. When responding to getResolvedTemplateType()
requests it wants to correct this length mismatch (by duplicating the
map and filling in the missing template values slots with UNKNOWN_TYPE)
so that arbitrary index accesses will be safe.

But the act of duplicating a TemplateTypeMap and inserting UNKNOWN_TYPE
triggers new (and also expensive) type comparisons.

If the types being dealt with are nested templatized types, the result is
a super-linear explosion of back and forth cross talk between the acts of
subtype checking and TemplateTypeMap duplicating + UNKNOWN_TYPE padding.

The simple fix is to make arbitrary index access in
getResolvedTemplateType() safe not by duplicating and padding with
UNKNOWN_TYPE but to instead directly return UNKNOWN_TYPE if the index is
past the bounds of the template values list.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=130311549

jscomp/opensource/pom-*.xml: use <dependencyManagement> for select dependencies

Building a version of jscomp that shares a JVM with closure-templates and other
closure tools would be easier if we could eliminate some dependency mismatches.

There are two issues that I try to address here
1. The guava dependency is a SNAPSHOT dependency, and compiling against it
   links to new Preconditions.check* method that do not exist in stable builds
   even though the 19.x/20.x-SNAPSHOT are source compatible.
2. Closure templates requires protobuf-java:3.x.

This does not change the versions of any dependencies.
It simply moves the versions for protobuf-java and guava into a
<dependencyManagement> section in the parent POM, and introduces
properties to specify them.

I can then build a soy+csscomp compatible jscomp thus
mvn -f pom-main-unshaded verify -Dguava.version=19.0 -Dprotobuf.version=3.0.0-beta-2

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=129361949

Free up a slot in the Node class by removing the "last" property.  This is done by making the "previous" node list circular, so that "first.previous" returns the same value as "last".

Here the "next" list is left as a simple list terminating with a null.  Originally, I attempted to use also make this circular (as the symmetry with the previous list was appealing).  However, this change "getNext" from a simple property retrieval to a conditional and this function is hot enough that it caused a compile time performance regression.  In this version "getNext" remains unchanged and no performance impact was measurable.

This has the following coding implications:
- in the Node class "previous" and "getPrevious()" no longer produce the same value
- it is no longer possible to call "getPrevious" on a detached Node as the "first" child of the parent must be known.
- removeChildren() returns a circular list
- "Children" and "Child" methods can no longer be used interchangeably for a single detached Node
- it is no longer possible to add a "tail" portion of a detached list

This change has the following benefits:
- the correct Child/Children methods must be called for the node structure
