Stop guerrilla-patching Object.keys and friends.

Previously we monkey-patched them to try to fix Symbol so that Object.keys and Object.getOwnPropertyNames would not return polyfilled symbols, nor would they return the hidden WeakMap property.  In practice, as long as Symbols show up in exacly one of getOwnPropertyNames and getOwnPropertySymbols, we're probably okay.  Given that the guerrilla patches (a) add a lot more code, and (b) increase complexity and brittleness significantly, it's probably best to not do it here.

Don't polyfill setPrototypeOf at all in IE<11 since it's not possible.

Previously we polyfilled it with a method that always threw or returned false.  But Babel seems to polyfill ES6 class-side inheritance by checking existence of Object.setPrototypeOf and using it if it's present.  So if we polyfill it then it will get used and break. In the old type checker, allow checking subtyping between typeA and typeB while ignoring null and undefined. Eg, in that setting,
(null|number) <: number
Foo<?Bar> <: Foo<!Bar>
Foo<!Bar> <: Foo<?Bar>

Most isSubtype functions just pass the flag around. The interesting places are:
- In union types, we ignore null and undefined
- In generics, we ignore null and undefined when checking for invariance

This CL only makes the changes in the type checker. It changes TypeValidator only in a single place, to allow testing the new subtyping relation. In follow-up CLs, we will funnel more TypeValidator and TypeCheck warnings through this mode, and enable the mode on a per-file basis.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=124966290

Migrate polyfills to ES5.

Previously the polyfills were written in ES6 and transpiled down to ES5 (and concatenated) into es6_runtime.js during the compiler's build, which requires us to check in generated code into our repository.  In order to eliminate this pre-compilation step (and use the separate files directly), we need to manually bring everything down to ES5, since the libraries are injected part-way through transpilation, so if a library is injected later that requires an earlier pre-processing, we'd have a bad time.  It might be possible in the future to move back to ES6 but we'd need to take care to ensure the injected libraries get the full transpilation treatment, and it's not clear that there would be any benefit since the whole point of these polyfills is that the browser *doesn't* support ES6, so they're only used when language_out < ES6.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=124899416

Tighten the dead property elimination deoptimzation

The previous implemention was a little too restrictive for most environments.
We now only trigger a deop if any of the following is true:

  a. A Object.defineProperty(...) where an aliased property name is being
  assigned to an aliased descriptor or the descriptor contains a getter/setter
  def.
  b. A Object.defineProperties where the last param is not an object literal.

To ensure safety, a property being defined with an aliased descriptor now just
blacklists that property name.

Finally, a new diagnostic error is introduced to report when there is a
pattern that triggers a critical deoptimization.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=121635064

Hoists constant like fields in J2CL generated code.

Some fields in Java are not compile time constants but eventually become assigned by a constant value after JsCompiler optimizations (e.g. System.getProperty calls and other operations that are statically evaluate-able).
As such fields are not compile time constants, they are both assigned in module scope as part of class declaration and also inside $clinit for initialization. As a result, JsCompiler refuses to inline and statically evaluate expressions that refers to field because it doesn't know when it will get initialized.

Technically, this is correct behavior since there are no guarantees that the initial value will be visible by others or not. However, such value is only visible in Java if there is a cycle in clinits and the field is accessed before initialization. That is almost always a bug and GWT never assumed this state is observable in its optimizations, yet nobody complained. Hence we consider it is safe to upgrade such field to a constant and make it inline-able as GWT does.

Work around GWT parser's handling of empty annotations.

Currently the GWT compiler simply hardcodes the empty string for JVM properties, but this leads to the parser's "unknown annotations" list being parsed as a singleton list containing only the empty string, which is bogus.  The upshot is that a particular angular.js file has some JSDoc with a CSS example containing "@-webkit" which gets parsed as an empty annotation and breaks rhino's source position information, causing an unchecked exception and crashing the parser.  This change fixes it in two different places: (1) we no longer add the empty string as a valid annotation name, and (2) even if an empty-named annotation is found by the JsDocInfoParser, it is considered invalid.  It also adds better debugging to the exception thrown by SourcePosition, which previously omitted the line number (which turned out to be very important in tracking down the issue).

Fix strange AST structure for destructing inside var/let/const.

Accomplish this by adding a new node, DESTRUCTURING_LHS, so that the
AST structure becomes:

    VAR
      DESTRUCTURING_LHS
        OBJECT_PATTERN
          OBJECT_PATTERN_CONTENTS
          MORE_OBJECT_PATTERN_CONTENTS
        RHS_EXPR

instead of the very weird previous AST of:

    VAR
      OBJECT_PATTERN
          OBJECT_PATTERN_CONTENTS
          MORE_OBJECT_PATTERN_CONTENTS
          RHS_EXPR

or PARAM where the destructuring patterns didn't contian the RHS exression.

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=118631481

Changes ClosureRewriteModule desugaring to allow inner class declaration before outer class. IE goog.module("foo.bar.Outer.Inner"); before goog.module("foo.bar.Outer");

Some of the major implementation points:
- instead of creating a goog.scope() rename every top level name in a module with a module$contents$Foo_ prefix to guarrantee uniqueness
- for goog.module()s rename the exports object to module$exports$Foo for global uniqueness
- rewrite all goog.require()s that reference a goog.module() (even inside of legacy scripts) to pull in the relevant module$exports$Foo object.
- inline all type aliases (both from goog.require()s and goog.forwardDeclare()s) in goog.module() files because goog.scope() did this and other passes have come to depend on it
- if a goog.module() declares legacy namespace add a "foo.Bar = module$exports$foo$Bar;" binary name to legacy name bridge at the end so that legacy goog.require()s resolve
- for every legacy script add a "var module$exports$foo$Bar = foo.Bar;" legacy name to binary name bridge at the end so that all goog.require() statements inside of goog.module() files can be desugared with the assumption that there is a binary name out there for it to reference
- replace JsDoc type names in the entire program to turn fully qualified type names that reference types in goog.module() files into resolvable "module$contents$Foo" references, as well as to account for type alias inlining in goog.module() file.

Fixes https://github.com/google/closure-compiler/issues/1264

Created by MOE: https://github.com/google/moe
MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=118179880

RefasterJS: Improve type matching of templates.

Instead of using loose matching, which can result in post-refactoring code that
does not type-check, use a strict type matching that matches only the exact
type specified in the template, or proper subtypes thereof.

To allow refactoring of code that does not quite match types as needed in the
after-template, as well as un-typed code, this CL changes RefasterJS to attempt
template matches strictly in the order in which the before-templates appear in
the template file.

This allows multiple before-templates of a given pattern to be specified with
successively more loose type matching, and appropriate after-templates.

See examples/navigational_xss_sinks.js for an extensive example.

MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=117947172

Rewrite the logic for folding comparisons in PeepholeFoldConstants

evaluateComparison() is now based on the three Abstract Operations
defined in the ES6 Specs: Abstract Relational Comparison [1],
Abstract Equality Comparison [2] and Strict Equality Comparison [3].

This fixes a handful of foldable cases that were not folded previously:

Cases like `0 < null` and `'hi' < null` are now folded.

String-string comparisons and string-number comparisions
like `'a' < 'b'` and `1 < '2'` are now folded.

Cases involving NaN are now folded.

As a bonus, a test case in testOptimizeSwitch() in
PeepholeRemoveDeadCodeTest now folds.

[1] http://www.ecma-international.org/ecma-262/6.0/#sec-abstract-relational-comparison
[2] http://www.ecma-international.org/ecma-262/6.0/#sec-abstract-equality-comparison
[3] http://www.ecma-international.org/ecma-262/6.0/#sec-strict-equality-comparison

Add GwtRunner, the GWT equivalent of CommandlineRunner

Changed JsComp.gwt.xml to use the SingleScriptLinker so that the GWT
compiler only outputs a single JavaScript file (jscomp.nocache.js).

Changed JsCompGwtMain to GwtRunner with "JSCompiler" exported as the
JavaScript name through JsInterop. Currently, GwtRunner supports a
limited set of compiler flags, including compilationLevel,
warningLevel, languageIn and languageOut among others.

To use the GWT version of the compiler, do a Maven build and include
"jscomp.nocache.js" from
target/closure-compiler-gwt-1.0-SNAPSHOT/jscomp/, Eg.:

<script src="jscomp.nocache.js"></script>
<script>
  var output = new JSCompiler().compile("var x;", {
      compilationLevel: 'ADVANCED',
      warningLevel: 'VERBOSE',
      languageIn: 'ECMASCRIPT5_STRICT',
      languageOut: 'ECMASCRIPT3'
  });
  console.log(output);
</script>

Note that GwtRunner doesn't automatically load the default externs yet,
so for now you need to manually provide the needed externs for ES6.

As an aside, the Maven build for closure-compiler-gwt is much faster
now that I removed most dependencies to gwt-user.jar.

Add checkNegatedLeftOperandOfInOperator to CheckSuspiciousCode

Check for negated left operand of the "in" operator
Eg:
  if (!a in b) {}
should almost always be
  if (!(a in b)) {}
or
  if (('' + !a) in b) {}
instead.

Negated left operand of the "in" operator usually indicates a programmer error.

Inspired by ESLint (https://github.com/eslint/eslint/blob/master/lib/rules/no-negated-in-lhs.js)

The bug has a number of facets to it.

  the API when passing in a handler that takes more than one parameter (as the
  one for the "set_at" event does.

[NTI] Don't do possibly-inexistent-property warnings on objects with optional properties.

When the receiver has an optional property and accesses it, we currently give two warnings, one for possibly-inexistent property and one because the context usually expects a type that doesn't include undefined. No point in giving two, we should warn only for the 2nd thing, and the programmer can check for undefined if they want. The 1st warning is also bad because they can't cast to a sensible type to avoid it, only to ?.

For unions of objects, we still give the possibly-inexistent-property warning. For those, the type doesn't include undefined when accessing the property.

Change usage of "*" to represent the unknown object in a Promise rejection to using "?".

"*" represents the top type in JSCompiler, whereas "?" represents the "any" type, i.e. an expression that cannot be typed and should not be checked.

The goal is to make arbitrary handler functions proper subtypes of the required function type, so that user code can (sort of cheatingly) pretend that the function type was bivariant.

MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=103326732

Fix typo in eval call in ClosureBundler.

The code currently does:

(0,eval("..."));

which is a "direct eval call" (See http://ecma262-5.com/ELS5_HTML.htm#Section_10.4.2
for details). I believe the intention was do an indirect call to get a global eval:

(0,eval)("...");

Since we weren't using a global eval before, it would be safer to just remove
the "0," to maintain the same behavior, but I believe doing the indirect call
is the prefered solution, since it more directly simulates the list of <script>
tags.

For example if a function wrapper was added or a "use strict" was added to the
outer script, this wold cause these direct eval calls to have separate
execution contexts, and functions/variables could not be shared (in fact this
is probably why change cr/93455279 was done, the "use strict" broken because of
this eval bug).

Adds an ES6 module style topological sort that allows circular references.

The current SortDependencies.java implementation is a breadth first
graph traversal that does not support circular dependencies.

ES6 modules support circular dependencies and perform a depth first graph
traversal.

This change adds support for the ES6 modules style ordering and turns it
on when JSComp is in ES6+ language-in mode.

To minimize side effects and reuse testing the change was performed by
turning SortedDependencies.java into an interface and creating 2
implementers.

MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=99025132

[NTI] Rework the finalization of namespaces, to allow adding class properties to nominal types after namespace finalization.

ProcessScope looks at scopes outer-to-inner, and we can't change this order without major changes (if at all). So, it's very common to see a constructor as the RHS of a @const assignment, without having seen all its class properties yet.

The reason we finalize a namespace is to convert it to a JSType. But when we compute the namespace type for the constructor, we care about the static properties (and the prototype properties), not the class properties (because the class properties are on the instances, not on the constructor). The class properties always live on RawNominalType.java, so we can keep adding them even if the raw type is contained in a JSType.

Minimal patch to allow custom CodeGenerator subclasses.

The built-in behavior of the compiler is to produce only the declared language_out source code. It does this with the primary CodeGenerator, as well as a subtype, TypedCodeGenerator, which additionally emits the declared types in JSDocs.

I would like to have my own subclass of CodeGenerator, to experiment with new language features for AtScript. In particular, I'm overriding the behavior of printing classes to emit an "interface" keyword rather than /** @interface */ class{}. I cannot do this in a CompilerPass because the syntax I'm generating is not valid ES6_TYPED and so it cannot be represented by the AST.

Automated g4 rollback of changelist 80781799.

*** Reason for rollback ***

This change starts an awful chain of consequences that leads to the current type system's distinction of declared and inferred record types.As is this causes some inferred record types to become declared record types.  It is unclear if it is time well spent to try to fix this. An alternate solution for goog.module is proposed.  However, that solution doesn't help ES6 modules or other module systems that naturally have a lot of type declaration aliases.  Native understanding of ES6 modules is, of course, the correct solution there.

Added a typedef for the jQuery AJAX setting object

The jQuery AJAX setting dictionary is a defined dictionary with known fields. When the various methods accept such a dictionary, they expect very specific properties (the developer can indeed add more properties, of course). Adding a typedef for this type of dictionary reduces the need to quote properties.
Currently, $.ajax({url: "/", beforeSend: function (){} ,cache: true,username: "d",xhrFields: {}}) compiles to $.ajax({url:"/",a:function(){},b:!0,c:"d",d:{}}), causing errors.

With the use of the typedef in the various functions, $.ajax({url: "/", type: "post"}) and friends will be minified without renaming the relevant properties, causing the code not to fail anymore.

Fixed generator structure to close in on the spec (https://people.mozilla.org/~jorendorff/es6-draft.html#sec-generatorfunction-objects).

1. The @@iterator ($$iterator property until symbols are supported) property of a Generator returns the generator itself (so that a caller can call f().next() or f().$$iterator().next() and it will be exactly the same).
2. 'return x' in a generator function should yield {value: x, done: true} to the caller, unlike 'yield x' which yields {value: x, done: false} as we know that execution of the generator is completed after a return.

MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=68991398

Improve CodingConvention#getPackageName impls + add tests.

Currently, the Google coding convention uses a source file's path as its package name. This is a problem for legacy directory layouts that place test files within test/ or testing/ subdirectories. (Closure places _test.js files in the same directory as source files, so it is unaffected.)

Currently, the default coding convention treats every source file as if it occupies a unique singleton package. If we added @package annotations to the Closure Library without changing this, compilation involving those parts of the library would fail. This CL makes the default coding convention use the source file's path as its package name, without the "test" exceptions of the Google coding convention.

Don't fold 'new RegExp(foo)' to 'RegExp(foo)' unless foo is a string literal.

If foo is a RegExp, then 'RegExp(foo)' returns foo unchanged [0], whereas 'new RegExp(foo)' constructs a new RegExp with the same pattern as foo, but without foo's state [1].

Fixes issue 1260.

[0] http://www.ecma-international.org/ecma-262/5.1/#sec-15.10.3.1
[1] http://www.ecma-international.org/ecma-262/5.1/#sec-15.10.4.1

Move the AngularJS externs files back into the Closure Compiler source tree.

While it's generally recommended to maintain externs together with the original
library, in the case of AngularJS this didn't really work: changes to the
externs are prone to break things, and we can only test those within Google.
There also seems to be little interest in maintenance of these outside of
Google, so most contributions come from inside and are much easier for users if
the source is maintained internally.

See also the corresponding AngularJS pull requests:
https://github.com/angular/angular.js/pull/5906 (v1.2/master)
https://github.com/angular/angular.js/pull/5907 (v1.0.x)

MOE_MIGRATED_REVID=50906661

Introduce an experimental option to use externs to export mutable properties and/or properties not on global names.

This differs from @expose in that it does not interfere with CollapseProperties or other optimizations that can ignore externs (generally, objects known not to escape) and pattern matching that doesn't expect GETELEM.

A finalized version of this combined with a @nocollapse annotation will allow us to remove @expose support.

Several simplification are made here:
1) only properties that would not otherwise have been legal to export are exportable using this new approach so this can't introduce problems for existing @export usage.
2) the properties are "exported" by creating synthetic properties on "Object.prototype".

Exporting on "Object.prototype" is not ideal as it prevents property disambiguation and thus renaming of the property globally, however it is sufficient to validate this approach. What should happen, once we have a mechanism for adding an synthetic interface declaration, is that each "class" would implement a specific "exports" interface just for that class.  Only object literal properties would be exported to Object.prototype.

Alternately, in an ES5 world these properties could be exported by introducing ES5 getters/setters for the properties to "alias" the name (this gets a little tricky as we would need to handle the case where the property is not actually renamed).

Update angular.js externs to show angular.bootstrap returns an angular.$injector.

Also update get and invoke to return {?} instead of {*}, since the ALL type is type-checked. In other words, this would cause a problem:

var injector = angular.bootstrap(blah);
injector.get('myFactory').newInstance();

Since the ALL type may represent a non-function type, so it can't be gauranteed to be a callable expression. On the other hand, {?} is never type checked, and allows callers to cast the return value.

Maybe if AngularJS team does closer integration with Closure compiler in the future they can map these to concrete types :)
